      <h2>How to Choose Based on Your Job Site</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>New construction / rough-in:</strong> The 100FT LED String Lights (4.7★) or ETL String Lights (4.6★) provide even ambient light across an entire floor. Add a Zetunlo tripod (4.6★) for task areas.</li>
        <li><strong>Remodels / occupied buildings:</strong> DEWALT DCL079B (4.8★) battery-powered — no cords to trip over, no breaker-tripping. Perfect where power is limited.</li>
        <li><strong>Basements / crawl spaces:</strong> HYPERLITE 50FT String Lights (4.6★) — compact length with climbing hooks for hanging from joists.</li>
        <li><strong>Night work / outdoor sites:</strong> Zetunlo or 21000L Tripod (4.6★/4.3★) — 21,000 lumens with IP66 weatherproofing will light up any outdoor area.</li>
        <li><strong>Concrete / wet work:</strong> 10000LM LED Work Light (4.6★) — IP66 rated, portable, high output for slab pours and outdoor finishing.</li>
        <li><strong>Finish work / painting:</strong> 2-Pack 50W LED Lights (4.8★) — 5000K daylight shows true paint colors and eliminates shadows in two rooms.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What to Look for When Comparing Job Site Lights</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lumens vs. area size —</strong> Don't over-buy or under-buy. A 10×10 bedroom needs ~3000 lumens; a 2000 sq ft floor needs 15,000–20,000+ lumens distributed across fixtures.</li>
        <li><strong>IP rating —</strong> Indoor dry jobs can use IP20 lights. Any outdoor, wet, or dusty site needs IP65/IP66. String lights at IP65 are fine for most construction.</li>
        <li><strong>Power source —</strong> Corded lights offer infinite runtime but limit mobility. Battery lights are flexible but need spare batteries and chargers on site.</li>
        <li><strong>Color temperature —</strong> 5000K daylight is the standard for construction. Warmer light (3000K) hides dust and imperfections — great for final walkthroughs, not for active work.</li>
        <li><strong>Linkability —</strong> String lights that daisy-chain save outlets. Look for linkable connectors rather than requiring separate cords per string.</li>
        <li><strong>Durability —</strong> Drop-tested, shatter-resistant lenses, and metal-reinforced mounting points matter on active job sites where lights get knocked over daily.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
      <p>For most contractors, the best setup is a combination: one or two <strong>Zetunlo 21000 Lumen Tripod Lights</strong> (4.6★) for broad area lighting, plus a set of <strong>100FT LED String Lights</strong> (4.7★) for hallways and perimeter areas. If you're a DEWALT user, the <strong>DCL079B</strong> (4.8★) is a must-have for your battery platform.</p>
      <p>On a budget? The <strong>2-Pack 50W LED Work Lights</strong> (4.8★) give you the highest-rated value in our comparison — two bright, durable lights that cover most standard job site needs without breaking the bank.</p>

